Prof. Nias is a researcher in computational social science in Spelman College's Course-Based Undergraduate Research Experiences (CURE) Program. Her current research focus is on developing educational computational technologies to promote cultural diversity and societal inclusion. She has also conducted research in human computer interaction, with a focus on child-computer interactions and mobile computing.
* [Nias, J.and Ruffin, M. CultureBot: A Culturally Relevant Humanoid Robot Dialogue Agent. In 2020 ACM Southeast Conference (ACMSE 2020), April 2–4, 2020, Tampa, FL, USA. ACM, New York, NY, USA.](https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/3374135.3385306)
* [Anthony, L., Brown, Q., Nias, J. and Tate, B. Children (and Adults) Benefit From Visual Feedback during Gesture Interaction on Mobile Touchscreen Devices. International Journal of Child-Computer Interaction, 2015.](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S2212868916000039)
* [Cummings, R. T., Dennis, S., Mack, N. A., Nias,J., and Gosha, K. Developing a Question Corpus for a Conversational Agent Designed to Prepare Interested Black Undergraduates for the Professoriate in STEM. Proceedings of the 2019 Research on Equity and Sustained Participation in Engineering, Computing, and Technology (RESPECT’19, Minneapolis).](https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/abstract/document/8985729)
